Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Chop the @sweet potato{1%large} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Halve or
quarter any large @cauliflower florets{300%g}.

Pop the sweet potato onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle},
season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}, then toss to coat. When the
oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{18-20%minutes}. Turn
halfway through.

Pop the cauliflower onto another large baking tray. Drizzle with oil, season
with salt and pepper, then toss to coat. Roast on the middle shelf of your
oven until golden and tender, ~{16-18%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Drain the
@king prawns{150%g}.

Once hot, add the prawns, @tomato puree{30%g}, @korma curry paste{50%g},
@north Indian style spice mix{1%sachet} and garlic. Stir-fry until fragrant,
~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw prawns.

Next, stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @honey{1%tbsp} and
@water{200%ml} for the curry. Season with salt and pepper.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium.

Simmer, stirring occasionally, until the sauce has thickened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Cook so the prawns are opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, put the @plain naans{2} onto a baking tray. Sprinkle with a little
water and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Once the curry sauce has thickened, remove from the heat. Stir through the
roasted veg and three quarters of the @soured cream{150%g}.

Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick. Taste and season with salt
and pepper if needed.

When everything's ready, share the roasted veg curry between your bowls. Finish
with a dollop of the remaining soured cream.

Slice up the naans and serve alongside for dipping and scooping. Enjoy!